My first dinner in DC! They say American food around here is good, and after walking down 17th and being repelled by ridiculously overpriced food, we found a place that had less than $10 burgers which was within all of our budgets. The menu had an array of sandwiches/typical diner food and lots of drinks- I think most people come here for the drinks and to sit outside and the breakfast/brunch might be better than dinner.  The interior is cozy, its like a more comfortable Applebees (if you've ever been there). I ordered the regular cheeseburger and tried the Trio sliders the second time. The food is standard, nothing too special about the burger and fries. Our service wasn't the greatest; my friend got the wrong order, our waitress was slow, and it took forever for her to bring the bill. Even the second time I went here I think they messed up orders and our waitress took forever to bring out the food and the bill.  It seems like a cool place to get a drink and the food is decent quality and reasonably priced, but it's not a must-go place in DC, especially with so many burger joints around. I'm looking forward to the burger places that the POTUS goes to! ;)

F&H is one of my favorite "divey" bars in DC. It's off the beaten path on 17th Street NW and offers a nice change to the typical DC bar scene. While it isn't exactly unique, there's something nice & comfortable about the wood paneled walls and leather seats. In the warmer months it is especially nice to sit outside. They do allow smoking outside though, so if that bothers you, then you may want to go inside.  But let's be honest, the happy hour is the real reason you want to go here. They offer great deals, especially on rail drinks. When you order a rum and coke, they bring you a decent sized glass of rum and a bottle of coke. Then you mix it yourself. You are essentially getting 1.5-2 drinks for the price of 1. My one real negative is that some of the waitresses are not the nicest/friendliest, but the bartenders have always been friendly and easy to talk to (should you find yourself drinking solo or waiting for someone, etc.) Overall, go here for their HH deals and comfortable/easy-going vibe, not so much for the food.

I've never actually been inside of the "lounge" part of Fox & Hounds (other than to use the restroom), but this is one of the best dive bars to sit outside on the patio and people watch. The service hasn't been especially remarkable, but Fox & Hounds makes it up in their mix-it-yourself beverages. Food is just okay.

I was there yesterday and it was not the Fox and Hound I knew. I found out my favorite bartender was no longer there, my burger was cooked wrong, they no longer carrying my brand of beer, and the place was empty except for one other person. I commented to the other customer about my unhappiness and they informed me it was under new ownership. Needless to say, I wont be back.
